page.title: 09THE PORT OF WISBECH.
page.content: A stranger to Wisbech might be excused for thinking that the town had little to do with the sea.However there are warehouses on the banks of the river some with a considerable history,and Wisbech for its size has long been a prosperous port, at times exceeding Kings Lynn in importance.At the beginning of the railway age the tonnage of cargo handled equalled anywhere in the region ,and today Wisbech shares in the general prosperity of all the east coast ports. Despite the fact that the port lies at the head of a narrow tidal passage some14 miles from the open sea Wisbech handles on average 320 ships a year.Ships are restricted to 75 m.in length to assist turning in the narrow river,and to 1500 tonnes by the bar at the Fenland Buoy.
